All that came together so that one day a very large man with a bowtie came into infant me's hospital room, put HIS ENTIRE HAND IN MY MOUTH, took it out, said "this i can fix" and then did. Dr degoose (not correct spelling) was my surgeon untill I was maybe 5

But it used to be a early and pioneering burns and plastics hospital, specializing in maxeofacial surgery. Their work with people coming home from WW1 really brought the field, as it was quite crude in most of the western world.

I lucked out. By being  born where I was (right across from the asb arena, the hospital was torn down tho) I fell into the catchment for middlemore hospital. Middlemore is a pretty old hospital,(I've always wanted to stay in the old bit I bet it's super haunted)

The blue book was really important, because we were replacing the old resources that cleft parents were given. My mother remembers being horrorfied at these pictures of the pretty crude work done on many cleft kids, and the before and afters.

I've been the older person. I met a woman whos son was in my mums scout troupe, who had been given the blue book with my pictures in it and an article written by my mum on dealing with acid reflux in cleft kids.

Unless you know a few characteristics of the cleft face, weather full facial or just lip or pallete, its pretty easy to spot. Flat front-face, underbite, no filtrum, smooth upper lip, no cupids bow sometimes wider set eyes, as the facial bones come together during development.

I was a weird kid and had really strong special interests as a very young person, and my family all looked at me and because it was the normal, they just shrugged and got me books in history for Christmas

Every day I remember that someone I idolized, someone who had been in the tombs whos walls I had poured over for hours. 
To this day I remember that kindness she gave to me, and I want to spend the rest of my time giving out kindness like that.

But she did. She put time from her day, from her life, to write an email to a autistic little kid who loved ancient Egypt more than anything. She wished me luck and thanked me for the email. Theres no way she would remember it, but I do.

My parents let me watch as history Channel and other documentarys, kept me well supplied with books and magazine articles, she was a familiar face. I never expected her to reply, since she is a world renowned historian who has seen things and held things i will never get to.

When I was a child, my life revolved around archeology and history, I wanted to become one so badly, so my parents helped me write an email to Dr Salima Ikram, who was my favorite Egyptologist, and my role model since I was very very small.

If you're like many disabled people, your mobility devices are a psychological extension of your body, as well as physically. You grow attached, they mold to you, you learn all of its quirks. It feels emotional and painful because that's you! That a part of you, and its broken

Im lucky, my wheelchair is from a very small family business (movingstar is fucking amazing check them out. Nz business, fantastic people, incredible customer service) and they would probably be able to help me if my chair was damaged, but its not certain or the norm for us.

As most disabled people know, many of our tools were very expensive single purchases, or were wheedled out of therapists to try and offer what little help they can, often by therapists long since left the Healthcare industry.

Im really greatful that with the bus, because im so mobile, I can transport my own wheelchair, because I will not let my chair out of my sight. Im terrorfied of it being damaged or broken and not being able to replace or repair it.
